This is a first shot for get_network_instances for IOS. The expected output doesn't make any sense to me so maybe we can clarify a few things here:

Expected output:
```
    u’MGMT’: {
        u’name’: u’MGMT’, u’type’: u’L3VRF’, u’state’: {
            u’route_distinguisher’: u‘123:456’,
        }, u’interfaces’: {
            u’interface’: {
                u’Management1’: {}
            }
        }
    } u’default’: {
        u’name’: u’default’, u’type’: u’DEFAULT_INSTANCE’, u’state’: {
            u’route_distinguisher’: None,
        }, u’interfaces: {
            u’interface’: {
                u’Ethernet1’: {} u’Ethernet2’: {} u’Ethernet3’: {} u’Ethernet4’: {}
            }
        }
    }
}
```

A few questions:
- the doc says `Return a dictionary of network instances (VRFs) configured, including default/global`: I don't think this can apply to Cisco.
- the name of the VRF is the key of the main dictionnary, why do we need to repeat it in the inner dictionnary ?
- what is expected for the type ? I just put L3VRF everywhere, I don't think this makes sense for Cisco.
- 'state' is a dictionnary that contains a single parameter (route distinguisher)
- interface is a dictionnary containing each interface as a key and a empty dictionnary as a value, why not just a list of interfaces ?

Overall, this function is hard to code for Cisco as-is. I guess we can change it, or maybe have a different function for Cisco VRF (get_vrf) as Juniper and Cisco handle VRF very differently. For Cisco, we would need to know which route-targets are imported/exported, and which route-maps as well, that information is missing right now. This route-target information would be per-AFI, i.e ipv4 unicast, ipv6 unicast, ipv4 multicast, ipv6 multicast.

Added a property nodeContextMenuItems to the tf-graph and tf-graph-scene components. This optional property is an array of `contextmenu.ContextMenuItem`s. This property offers an API for developers to extend the context menu by adding custom items, each with a title and a callback.

See `getContextMenu` for an example array:

```ts
let menu = [{
  title: (d): string => {
    return getIncludeNodeButtonString(node.include);
  },
  action: (elm, d, i) => {
    sceneElement.fire('node-toggle-extract', {name: node.name});
  }
}];
```

Screenshot (Here, we add a "Foo" context menu item):

![wtfio66dqk6](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4221553/30001293-550d9e2e-903e-11e7-805c-083a3a5803d0.png)

